```

In this example, TypeScript infers that the `greet` function takes a `name` parameter of type `string`, because the `greet` function is called with a parameter of type `string`, and the inferred type of the parameter is `string`.

In summary, TypeScript adds static typing to JavaScript by using type annotations and duck typing to define the types of variables, functions, and objects in a program. TypeScript also supports type inference, which allows TypeScript to guess the type of a variable, function, or object based on its value or context, which can help improve code maintainability and catch type errors at compile-time.
